To compute the Asset Turnover:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Asset Turnover}&=\frac{\text{Sales}}{\text{Total Assets}}\times 100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\text{\$1,000,000}}{\text{\$800,000}}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{1.25}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;;
**The asset turnover of the company is 1.25.**

To compute the equity multiplier:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Equity Multiplier}&=\text{Debt-to-Equity Ratio}+1\\[12pt]
&={0.95}+1\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{1.95}\\
\end{aligned}$$

&nbsp;
**The equity multiplier is 1.95.**

To determine the sustainable growth rate, let us first compute the return on equity:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Return on Equity}&=\text{Profit Margin}\times\text{Total Asset Turnover}\\[5pt]
&\times\text{Equity Multiplier}\\[12pt]
&={7.3\%}\times{1.25}\times{1.95}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{0.18}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The return on equity is 0.1779.**

Now, let us compute the retained earnings:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Retained Earnings}&=\text{Net Income}-\text{Dividend}\\[12pt]
&={\$73,000}-{\$24,000}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$49,000}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The retained earnings is \$49,000.**

Now, let us compute the retention ratio:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Retention Ratio}&=\frac{\text{Retained Earnings}}{\text{Net Income}}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$49,000}{\$73,000}\times100\\[12pt]
&={0.67}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{67\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The retention ratio is 67\%.**

### Compute the sales using the derived formula.

Sales are calculated by dividing the net income by the profit margin.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Sales}&= \dfrac{ \text{\$73,000.00}}{\text{73\%}}\\[15pt]

&= \boxed{\textbf{\$1,000,000.00}}

\end{aligned}
$$


Therefore, the total sales are $**1,000,000.00**.

### Derive the calculation of total assets from the capital intensity ratio.

Computation of total assets can be derived from the formula of capital intensity ratio.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Total Assets}&= \text{Sales} \times \text{Capital intensity ratio}


\end{aligned}
$$

### Compute the total assets using the derived formula.

Total assets are calculated by multiplying the sales with the capital intensity ratio.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Total Assets}&= \text{Sales} \times \text{Capital intensity ratio}\\[15pt]

&= \$1,000,000.00 \times 0.80\\[15pt]

&= \boxed{\textbf{\$800,000.00}}


\end{aligned}
$$


Therefore, the total assets are $800,000.00.

### First, compute the asset turnover.

**Asset turnover** -It measures the efficiency of the company's assets in producing sales or profit.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Asset Turnover}&= \dfrac{ \text{Net Sales}}{\text{Total Assets}}\\[15pt]

&= \dfrac{\$1,000,000.00}{\$800,000.00}\\[15pt]

&= \boxed{\textbf{1.25}}
\end{aligned}
$$


Therefore, the asset turnover is **1.25**.

### Compute the equity multiplier.

The equity multiplier can be derived from the debt ratio.

The  formula of the deb ratio

$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Debt Ratio}&= 1 - \text{1/Equity Multiplier}


\end{aligned}
$$

### Derive the debt ratio to equity multiplier formula.

The derived formula is as follows.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Equity Multiplier}&= 1 + \text{Debt to Equity Ratio}


\end{aligned}
$$

### Compute the equity multiplier.

From the derived formula, we can now compute the equity multiplier. The debt-equity ratio is 0.95.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Equity Multiplier}&= 1 + \text{Debt to Equity Ratio}\\[15pt]

&= 1+ 0.95\\[15pt]

&= \boxed{\textbf{1.95}}

\end{aligned}
$$

### Compute the return on equity,

Now that the equity multiplier, asset turnover, and profit margin are available, we can compute the equity return.


$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Return on Equity}&= \text{Profit Margin} \times \text{Equity Multiplier}
\times \text{Asset Turnover}\\[15pt]

&= 7.3\% \times 1.95 \times 1.25\\[15pt]

&= 0.1779 \times 100\\[15pt]

&= \boxed{\textbf{17.79\%}}
\end{aligned}
$$


Therefore, the return on equity is **17.79%**.
